Part 1: K-Means Algorithm¶

Clustering is a process of partitioning a set of data (or objects) in a set of meaningful sub-classes, called clusters. The k-means algorithm is a widely used clustering technique that seeks to minimize the average squared distance between points in the same cluster. In other words, given a dataset X={x1,…,xM}X={x1,…,xM} where xi∈RNxi∈RN with MM samples of NN dimensions, we can describe it with KK clusters, each represented by a centroid μk∈RNμk∈RN, by minimizing the total squared distance between each point and its closest centroid with the following cost function,

J(μ1,…,μk)=K∑k=1∑xi∈ck|xi−μk|2(1)(1)J(μ1,…,μk)=∑k=1K∑xi∈ck|xi−μk|2

where ck∈{1,…,K}ck∈{1,…,K} is the cluster label. This is an NP-hard problem, however, the k-means algorithm provides a local search solution for through an iterative procedure proposed in the 1980's by Stuart P. Lloyd.

K-Means Algorithm¶

For a deeper description of K-Means and its applications, refer to the Clustering slides from the Applied Machine Learning Course. In this assignment, we will follow the steps of the k-Means algorithm shown on slide 25 of the class. Given a fixed number of KK clusters we will go through the following steps:

  1. Randomly initialize the centroids μ={μ1,…,μK}μ={μ1,…,μK}
  2. Calculate distances from each data point xixi to each centroid μkμk.
  3. Assignment Step: For each cluster ck∈{1,…,K}ck∈{1,…,K}, set the cluster CkCk to be the set of points in XX that are closer to μkμk than any other cluster centroid.
  4. Update Step: For each cluster ck∈{1,…,K}ck∈{1,…,K}, set μkμk to be the centroid of all points assigned to Ck:μk=1|Ck|∑x∈CkxCk:μk=1|Ck|∑x∈Ckx
  5. Go back to step 2 and repeat until the cluster centroids μkμk stabilize (i.e. error between current and previous estimates of μkμk are below a threshold thres=1e-4 or the maximum number of iterations (MaxIter) is reached.

Interesting Properties of K-Means¶

  • There are always KK clusters.
  • The clusters do not overlap.
  • Each member of a cluster is closer to its cluster than to any other cluster.

Step 1. Centroid μkμk Initialization¶

In the k-means algorithm, the initialization of the centroids μkμk is one of the most important steps, if the centroids are initialized far away from the expected cluster centers, the algorithm might not be able to reach the expected solution. Hence, several methods have been proposed to initialize the centroids. In this assignment, we should implement two initialization methods:

  • random sampling: Sample KK data points from XX at random.
  • random in a range: Select KK data points uniformly at random from the range of XX; i.e. if we have a 2D dataset we select points at random between [min(X1),min(X2)]→[max(X1),max(X2)][min(X1),min(X2)]→[max(X1),max(X2)]

Step 2. Calculate Distances between XX and centroids μkμk¶

Many clustering algorithms (specifically k-means) rely on a metric or "distance" function between the data points. While one typically uses the Euclidean distance as a metric in RNRN, it actually comes from a more general class of metrics, i.e. the Minkowski metric:

Lp(x,x′)=(∑Ni=1|xi−x′i|p)1/p,Lp(x,x′)=(∑i=1N|xi−xi′|p)1/p,

otherwise known as the LPLP norm. From this norm, we can recover three important distances used in the machine learning applications. For example, when p=1p=1 we recover the L1L1 norm, also known as the Manhattan distance:

dL1(x,x′)=||x−x′||1=N∑i=1|xi−x′i|,(2)(2)dL1(x,x′)=||x−x′||1=∑i=1N|xi−xi′|,

this distance gives the shortest path between xx and x′x′ on a grid aligned to the data's coordinate system, also called the grid or rectilinear distance. When p=2p=2 we get the L2L2 norm otherwise known as the Euclidean distance, the most common metric in literature for RNRN:

dL2(x,x′)=||x−x′||2= ⎷N∑i=1|xi−x′i|2.(3)(3)dL2(x,x′)=||x−x′||2=∑i=1N|xi−xi′|2.

The Euclidean distance measures the distance between two points as the length of a straight line between them. Finally, p=∞p=∞ yields the L∞L∞ norm:

dL∞(x,x′)=||x−x′||∞=maxi|xi−x′i|,(4)(4)dL∞(x,x′)=||x−x′||∞=maxi|xi−xi′|,

which measures the maximum distance between dimensions.

Step 3. Assignment Step: Centroid Responsibility¶

After calculating the distances from each point of X={x1,…,xM}X={x1,…,xM} to each centroid of μ={μ1,…,μK}μ={μ1,…,μK}, we should assign points to their closest cluster centroids. Algorithmically, we do this by using the concept of responsibility; i.e. the cluster centroid μkμk closest to a data point xixi is responsible for that data point, the closest centroid can be found as follows,

ki=argmink{d(xi,μk)},(5)(5)ki=argmink{d(xi,μk)},

where ki∈{1,…,k}ki∈{1,…,k} is the id or label of the closest cluster. The responsibility of each kk-th cluster for data point xixi can then be computed as follows,

rki={1ifki=k0otherwise(6)(6)rik={1ifki=k0otherwise

If a tie happens (i.e. two centroids are equidistant to a data point), one assigns the data point to the centroid with the smallest winning cluster size.

Step 4. Update Step: Recompute centroids¶

We must then adjust the centroids of CkCk to be the means of all data points assigned to them, this is called the maximization step and is computed as follows:

μk=∑irkixi∑irki(7)(7)μk=∑irikxi∑irik

Step 5. Check for convergence¶

We then go back to step 2 and repeat the process until the clusters are stable (i.e. there is no change between μ(t)μ(t) and μ(t−1)μ(t−1) where tt is the iteration, for a certain number of steps given by the variable MaxTolIter) or the maximum MaxIter is reached.

TASK 4: Implement check_convergence.m function (1pts)¶

The function has the following signature:

In [ ]:
function [has_converged, tol_iter] = check_convergence(Mu,Mu_previous,iter,tol_iter,MaxIter,MaxTolIter,tolerance)

It should return true in has_converged if either one of the two following conditions is met:

  • The number of iterations iter has passed the maximum number of iterations MaxIter
  • The number of iterations tol_iter for which μ(t)≈μ(t−1)μ(t)≈μ(t−1) has passed the maximum number of iterations MaxTolIter

If there is no convergence but μ(t)≈μ(t−1)μ(t)≈μ(t−1) is verified, then tol_iter should be incremented. tolerance is used to check the approximate equality between μ(t)μ(t) and μ(t−1)μ(t−1) as strict equality should never be used due to numerical approximations.

Part 2: Metrics, and Semi-Supervised Clustering¶

In this part of the assignment, you will define some metrics that will help you choosing the optimal number of clusters. You will then apply it to a high dimensionnal dataset.

Evaluation Metrics for Clustering¶

How do we determine the best clustering? For this, we can use a set of metrics which are used to evaluate clustering performance. Following we provide the equations of the three clustering metrics that you will implement for k-means. For more explanations on the metrics, refer to the slides on clustering evaluation metrics from the Advanced Machine Learning course.

  • RSS, the Residual Sum of Squares is in fact the cost function that k-means is trying to minimize, hence
RSS=K∑k=1∑xi∈ck|xi−μk|2(8)(8)RSS=∑k=1K∑xi∈ck|xi−μk|2
  • AIC metric is a maximum-likelihood measure that penalizes for model complexity AIC=−2lnL+2BAIC=−2ln⁡L+2B where BB is the number of parameters and LL the likelihood of the model. Even though the K-means algorithm does not provide a likelihood estimate of the model it can be formulated as a metric based on RSSRSS as follows:
AICRSS=RSS+2B,(9)(9)AICRSS=RSS+2B,

where B=(K∗N)B=(K∗N) for KK clusters and NN dimensions.

  • BIC metric goes even further and penalizes for number of datapoints as well with the following equation BIC=−2lnL+ln(M)BBIC=−2ln⁡L+ln⁡(M)B. As in AICRSSAICRSS, we can formulate a BICBIC value based on the RSSRSS as follows:
BICRSS=RSS+ln(M)B,(10)(10)BICRSS=RSS+ln⁡(M)B,

where BB is as before and MM is the total number of datapoints.

TASK 6: Implement compute_metrics.m function (3pts)¶

The function has the following signature:

Choosing Optimal KK¶

To choose the optimal KK for your dataset, one can run K-Means by increasing monotonically the number of clusters and plotting the results. Since the output of K-Means is not deterministic, we should run K-Means for repeats times, generally 10, and take the mean or best of those runs as the result, in this implementation we will take the mean.

For the RSSRSS metric, the elbow or plateau method can be reliable for certain datasets. This method finds the optimal KK at the elbow of the curve, i.e. when the values stop decreasing rapidly. For the AICAIC and BICBIC metrics, the optimal KK is found as the minimum value in the curve.

As we can see, it is hard to identify the optimal KK for this dataset. Moreover, due to its high dimensionality, the result of a single K-Means run cannot be visualized. Hopefully, one can use some dimensionnality reduction technique such as PCA to later cluster in a lower dimensional space

Cluster the projected data¶

One of the advantages of PCA is not only that it projects the dataset to a lower dimensional space, but also, since it projects the dataset onto a new basis (guided by maximum variance) it can make the dataset more linearly separable and hence easier to cluster! By running the third code block of tp2_kmeans_part2.m, we will apply PCA to the digits dataset and project it to a 4-D sub-space. Then we evaluate K-means on this lower-dimensional space.

In [44]:

As can be seen, the clustering metrics on the lower-dimensional space seem to yield a more decisive optimal KK.

In [51]:

Semi-Supervised Clustering with F1-measure¶

When a subset of labels are available for the dataset we are clustering, we can apply an external metric to evaluate the results of our clustering algorithm. The external metric we will use in this practical is the F1-measure. For more details on this, refer to the slides on evaluation of clustering methods from the Applied Machine Learning Course.

The F1-measure can be estimated by using the following equations:

F1(C,K)=∑ci∈C|ci|Mmaxk{F1(ci,k)}(11)(11)F1(C,K)=∑ci∈C|ci|Mmaxk{F1(ci,k)}F1(ci,K)=2R(ci,k)P(ci,k)R(ci,k)+P(ci,k)(12)(12)F1(ci,K)=2R(ci,k)P(ci,k)R(ci,k)+P(ci,k)R(ci,k)=nik|ci|(13)(13)R(ci,k)=nik|ci|P(ci,k)=nik|k|(14)(14)P(ci,k)=nik|k|

MM = number of labeled datapoints CC = set of classes KK = number of clusters niknik = number of members of cici and of cluster kk

From the clustered labels and the ground truth labels in cluster_labels and class_labels respectively it should return the four components of the F1-measure as calulated with the above equations.

Part 3: Application as an unsupervised recommendation system¶

Recommendation systems are everywhere now, from the platform of video streaming that proposes you to watch a new show, to the posts you see on social media. They all have something in common, there are supposed to be personnalized and adapted to your taste.

In this last part we will construct such a recommendation system to help you build decks in Magic the Gathering (MTG) trade card game. The interest for this game lies in the fact that there is a huge amount of different cards to choose from, and a similarly huge base of players to take inspiration from. Do not worry if you have never heard of the game before, as k-means is unsupervised we can even do that without having a clue about the structure of the game or even what cards look like. The only thing we need to know is that each card has a name and that two different cards do not have the same name. We will just look at the cards that top player choose hoping that they know what are the good associations between them.

First we will load a dataset of decks from mtgProject Github repository. The dataset contains 777777 decks from top MTG players. A deck is a list of 6060 cards, where a card can only appear in 44 examplary in the same deck. If you look at the loaded data table you will notice that it is a cell array containing strings and, as you know, strings are difficult to handle. Therefore the first step will be to rearrange the data.

Data preparation¶

In order to be able to apply K-Means on the dataset, we first need to prepare the data by transforming the cell array as a numerical matrix. We will go even further by applying a special transformation.

Our interest is to be able to recommend cards to complete a partially filled deck. We will first transform the dataset to have for each cards its frequency of appearance in the different decks. For example, if we have 1010 decks and a card appears 33 times in the second deck and 11 time in the seventh, the corresponding row for that card will be:

In [ ]:
[0,3,0,0,0,0,1,0,0,0]

At the end we should obtain a N×MN×M matrix where NN is the number of unique cards in the dataset and MM the number of decks, i.e. 777777 here.

The function should return both the transformed data in X and the array of unique card names in unique_cards.

Clustering and card recommendation¶

The next step is to apply K-Means on the previously transformed dataset. We will arbitrary choose K=8K=8. We obtain 88 clusters corresponding to 88 different archetype of decks. Applying K-Means on the dataset gives the set of centroids μkμk, core of the recommendation system.

In [ ]:
[labels, Mu, ~] =  kmeans(X, K, init, type, MaxIter, plot_iter);

The next step is to extract a recommended card from the centroids of the clusters. Let us assume that we have a deck containing for now only one 367 card. To represent this, we create a deck as vector of size NN, full of zeros except for the card of interest.

In [ ]:
deck = zeros(length(unique_cards))
deck(367) = 1

In case we have multiple times the same card, the line contains the number of times we own that card.

In [ ]:
deck = zeros(length(unique_cards))
deck(367) = 2
deck(48) = 1

For recommending a card, we should look at the centroids μkμk at the rows corresponding to the card in our deck and select the cluster

We should look at the row corresponding to this card in μkμk and select the cluster for which the value is the closest to 11.

In this case the distance should be the sum of the distance for each card. The easiest way to achieve this would be to use the distance_to_centroids function implemented earlier. However it cannot be applied directly on the deck vector as this vector represent a partially filled deck. In distance_to_centroids, we assume that the sample comes from the same distribution as the cluster, i.e. that we have a full deck. This is not the case in our situation. Therefore, we need to create a new distance function.

Task 11: Implement deck_distance.m function (2pts)¶

The function has the following signature:

In [ ]:
function [dist] = deck_distance(deck, Mu, type);

You can see this new distance function as the distance with subset of the centroids where the subset corresponds to non-zero cards. You should reuse the distance_to_centroids function but be careful to correctly perform it on a subset of deck and Mu.

Recommending the next card¶

Thanks to the previous distance function we can now estimate the archetype of our ongoing deck, i.e. the closest cluster. From this cluster, we can recommend any other cards. There is not much we can do without adding prior knowledge so we will just sort the cards in descending order based on the values in the chosen μkμk.
